Que es R?


“R is a language and environment for statistical computing and graphics”

Source: R-project.org

Que es R?

  • ggplot2 es un paquete de visualizacin de datos para R
    • Desarrollado por Hadley Wickham
    • Inspirado por Leland Wilkinson de “La Gramtica de Grficos”
    • Ofrece una filosofa de organizacin para la construccin de grficos - un enfoque estructurado para graficacin

“The emphasis in ggplot2 is reducing the amount of thinking time by making it easier to go from the plot in your brain to the plot on the page.”

Wickham, 2012

La filosofa de ggplot2

  • Un ggplot2 grfico se construye a partir unos pocos elementos bsicos:
    • Datos: the raw data you want to plot
    • Esttica: including Mapping por ejemplo, which variable is on the x-axis? the y-axis? Should the color/size/position of the plotted data that be mapped to some variable?
    • Geometras: the geometric shapes that represent the data
    • Estadsticas: statistical transformations that are used to summarize the data

Source: Hopper (2014)

Cmo instalar ggplot?


install.packages('ggplot2')
library('ggplot2')


Make sure you have the most recent version of R to get the most recent version of ggplot2

Los datos: US estados

data(state)
states.data <- as.data.frame(state.x77)
states.data$states <- rownames(states.data)
colnames(states.data)[4] <- "Life.Exp"
Population Income Illiteracy Life.Exp Murder HS Grad states

Arizona 2212 4530 1.8 70.55 7.8 58.1 Arizona

Los datos: US estados


  • Population: population estimate as of July 1, 1975
  • Income: per capita income (1974)
  • Illiteracy: illiteracy (1970, percent of population)
  • Life Exp: life expectancy in years (196971)
  • Murder: murder and non-negligent manslaughter rate per 100,000 population (1976)
  • HS Grad: percent high-school graduates (1970)

    Source: US Census Bureau via R datasets

Cmo trazar sus datos: quick plot

qplot(Income, Life.Exp, data = states.data)

Cmo trazar sus datos: quick plot

qplot(Income, Life.Exp, data = states.data, main = "Income v. Life Expectancy")

Caractersticas bsicas de ggplot2

  • Scatter Plot
  • Line Graph
  • Bar Graph

Scatter Plot

ggplot(data = states.data, 
       aes(x = Income, 
           y = Life.Exp)) + 
  geom_point() +
  ggtitle("Income v. Life Expectancy")

Scatter Plot

Scatter Plot - start x-axis at 1000

ggplot(data = states.data, 
       aes(x = Income, 
           y = Life.Exp)) + 
  geom_point() +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(1000, 7000))

Scatter Plot - start x-axis at 1000

Scatter Plot - start x-axis at 1000 (breaks every 1000), y-axis at 60

ggplot(data = states.data, 
       aes(x = Income, 
           y = Life.Exp)) + 
  geom_point() +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(1000, 7000), 
                     breaks = seq(1000, 7000, 1000)) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(60, 75))

Scatter Plot - start x-axis at 1000 (breaks every 1000), y-axis at 60

Scatter Plot - color mapped to state

ggplot(data = states.data, 
       aes(x = Income, 
           y = Life.Exp, 
           color = states)) + 
  geom_point()

Scatter Plot - color mapped to state

Line Graph

ggplot(data = states.data, 
       aes(x = Income, 
           y = Life.Exp)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_line()

Line Graph

Line Graph - specific color/size

ggplot(data = states.data, 
       aes(x = Income, 
           y = Life.Exp)) + 
  geom_point(color = 'red', size = 5) + 
  geom_line(color = 'blue')

Line Graph - specific color/size

Line Graph - points on top, different line type & point shape

ggplot(data = states.data, 
       aes(x = Income, 
           y = Life.Exp) + 
  geom_line(color = 'blue', 
            linetype = 'dashed') +
  geom_point(color = 'red', 
             size = 2, 
             shape = 15)

Line Graph - points on top, different line type & point shape

Bar Graph - simple

three.states <- states.data[states.data$states == "California" | states.data$states == "New York" | states.data$states == "Texas", ]

*Vamos a utilizar tres estados de los datos: California, Nueva York y Texas

Population Income Illiteracy Life.Exp Murder HS Grad states
California 21198 5114 1.1 71.71 10.3 62.6 California
New York 18076 4903 1.4 70.55 10.9 52.7 New York
Texas 12237 4188 2.2 70.90 12.2 47.4 Texas

Bar Graph - simple

ggplot(data = three.states, 
       aes(x = states, 
           y = Population)) +
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity')

Bar Graph - simple

Bar Graph - simple, transparent background

ggplot(data = three.states, 
       aes(x = states, 
           y = Population)) +
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity') +
  theme(panel.background = element_blank())

Bar Graph - transparent background

Bar Graph - stacked

three.states$Category <- ifelse(three.states$states == "Texas", "Texas", "California/New York")

Tenemos una variable, *Categora, que pone los datos en dos categoras: “Texas” si es de Texas, y “California / New York” si es de California o Nueva York

Population Income Illiteracy Life.Exp Category
California 21198 5114 1.1 71.71 California/New York
New York 18076 4903 1.4 70.55 California/New York
Texas 12237 4188 2.2 70.90 Texas

Bar Graph - stacked

ggplot(data = three.states, 
       aes(x = Category, 
           fill = states)) +
  geom_bar(position = 'stack') +
  theme(panel.background = element_blank())

Bar Graph - stacked

Bar Graph - stacked

ggplot(data = three.states, 
       aes(x = Category, 
           y = Illiteracy,
           fill = states)) +
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity', 
           position = 'stack') +
  theme(panel.background = element_blank())

Bar Graph - stacked

Caractersticas avanzadas

  • Facetting
  • Fitted Lines
  • Text Labels

Facetting

  • Facetting allows you to split up your data in one or two variables
  • facet_grid() places one or two variables in either vertical or horizontal directions
  • facet_wrap() places facets next to each other, wrapping with a certain # of rows and/or columns
facet_grid(vertical ~ horizontal)

facet_wrap(~ variable, nrow = ___, ncol = ___)

Facetting

states.data$Pop.Under.2000 <- ifelse(states.data$Population < 2000, "Pop Under 2000", "Pop Above 2000")


  • I created a variable, Pop.Under.2000, which shows whether the population (in thousands) is under 2000 or above 2000

Facetting

ggplot(data = states.data, 
       aes(x = Income, 
           y = Life.Exp)) + 
  geom_point() +
  facet_grid(. ~ Pop.Under.2000)

Facetting

ggplot(data = states.data, 
       aes(x = Income,

Fitted Lines

Fitted Lines

ggplot(data = states.data, 
       aes(x = Income, 
           y = Life.Exp)) +

Fitted Lines

Text Labels 

ggplot(data = states.data, 
       aes(x = Income, 
           y = Life.Exp)) +
        geom_text(aes(label = states))
